[Anaplasmosis in people
---------------------
- Signs and symptoms of anaplasmosis typically begin within 1-2 weeks after the bite of an infected tick. Note that tick bites are usually painless, and many people do not remember being bitten.
- See your healthcare provider if you become ill after having been bitten by a tick or having been in the woods or in areas with high brush where ticks commonly live.

Early illness
Early signs and symptoms (days 1-5) are usually mild or moderate and may include:
- fever, chills
- severe headache
- muscle aches
- nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, loss of appetite

Late illness
Rarely, if treatment is delayed, or if there are other medical conditions present, anaplasmosis can cause severe illness. Prompt treatment can reduce your risk of developing severe illness. Signs and symptoms of severe (late-stage) illness can include:
- respiratory failure
- bleeding problems
- organ failure
- death

Risk factors for severe illness:
- delayed treatment
- age: being older puts you at risk
- weakened immune system: People with weakened immune systems (such as those receiving some cancer treatments, individuals with advanced HIV infection, prior organ transplants, or people taking some medications) are at risk for severe illness.
Source: https://www.cdc.gov/anaplasmosis/symptoms/index.html

Anaplasmosis in human beings, also referred to as human granulocytic anaplasmosis (HGA), is a bacterial disorder transmitted by a species of bacteria named _Anaplasma phagocytophilum_. The condition was earlier referred to as human granulocytic ehrlichiosis (HGE).

Lyme disease and other serious diseases may be transmitted by ticks, but anaplasmosis should also be considered a serious disease. Tick diseases are distressing, uncomfortable, and sometimes deadly in severe cases. Hikers, those working in agriculture, forest workers, or even vacationers take these parasites seriously.

As it's vacation season, and now that people are seeking the outdoors more as the COVID-19 lockdown in many areas is lessening, the ticks will be hungry and anxious for your ankles, legs, and any other place they can crawl to on you or your pet. On humans, ticks easily migrate to where a waistband may be, or even up to your armpits. So be sure to check all of you, even your head.

Anaplasmosis in animals
---------------------
Anaplasmosis is a little different in animals, although it is still transmitted by ticks.

Anaplasmosis is a tick-borne disease caused by the infectious bacterial organism _A. phagocytophilum_. It is transmitted through bites of the deer tick (also known as the black-legged tick) and western black-legged tick. A lesser form of anaplasmosis is caused by _Anaplasma platys_ and is transmitted by the brown dog tick. Anaplasmosis has been reported worldwide in a wide variety of animals.

The more common form of anaplasmosis, caused by _A. phagocytophilum_, often causes lameness, joint pain, fever, lethargy (lack of energy, general malaise), and anorexia (lack of appetite). Most infected dogs will have signs for 1-7 days; however, some will have no signs or only minor signs. Less common clinical signs include vomiting, diarrhea, coughing, and labored breathing. Anaplasmosis is less common in cats, but similar clinical signs can be seen if they do get this disease. Rarely, neurological signs such as seizures have been reported.

Infection with _A. platys_ can cause cyclic thrombocytopenia, a condition where there is a periodic decrease in platelets (circulating cells helping the blood-clotting process). Clinical disease is often mild, but some dogs may develop bruising or bleeding (including nosebleeds), especially during the early stages of infection when platelet counts may be at their lowest.

Dogs with anaplasmosis often have many of the same signs as those with Lyme disease, and infection with both agents (co-infection) is not uncommon. Both Lyme disease and anaplasmosis are commonly found in the same geographic location and are transmitted by the same tick species.

Several types of tests to diagnose exposure or an infection are available. Exposure to _Anaplasma_ spp. can be detected in your veterinary clinic using a special test kit. Other tests, including enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA), indirect fluorescent antibody (IFA), and polymerase chain reaction (PCR), are available to help your veterinarian determine if active infection is present. These tests are sent to an outside lab. In addition, the organism can sometimes be seen through a microscope during peak phases of infection.

Your veterinarian will discuss the various test options and determine which diagnostic protocol is best for your dog's condition.

The treatment for canine anaplasmosis, the antibiotic doxycycline, is the same as for other closely related tick-borne infections, including ehrlichiosis and Lyme disease. Many infected dogs are treated for 2-4 weeks (the longer course more often if co-infected with Lyme disease). In the majority of cases, signs improve rapidly. Dogs are often markedly better 24-48 hours after therapy is begun, and the prognosis for clinical recovery is excellent.

Although most dogs clinically improve, it may be difficult to determine whether or not a dog is no longer infected. If a dog stops producing antibodies to the organism, this may indicate the organism has been cleared from the body. Even if a dog that was infected with anaplasmosis is treated and returns to normal, the dog may continue to test positive for the infection on subsequent blood tests. However, this does not mean the dog has an active infection, and a 2nd round of antibiotic therapy to try to obtain a negative blood test is generally not recommended.

Dogs from areas where anaplasmosis or Lyme disease are common have often been exposed to _A. phagocytophilum_ and have a positive antibody test result. It appears many dogs may have antibodies to _A. phagocytophilum_ without having any evidence of clinical disease. It has been shown that clinically healthy dogs may have persistent infection with _A. phagocytophilum_ and are chronically infected carriers of the organism. We do not know if these dogs will eventually become ill or not.

Current research suggests canine anaplasmosis is an acute disease occurring in dogs 1-2 weeks after infection through a tick bite. Because chronic infection has not been directly related to clinical disease, and because a therapeutic regimen effective in clearing the organism from an infected animal has not been established, treating clinically healthy, positive-testing animals is of questionable benefit and not generally recommended at this time.

However, a positive test result in a clinically healthy dog should not be disregarded. At a minimum, positive dogs should have an aggressive tick control program implemented to minimize exposure to ticks. It is clear that co-infection with 2 or more tick-borne agents is common, and dogs co-infected with Lyme disease (_Borrelia burgdorferi_), _A. phagocytophilum_, and _Anaplasma_ are nearly 2 times more likely to develop clinical disease than dogs infected with either agent alone. Your veterinarian will recommend a tick preventive best suited for your dog.

There is also some concern that chronically infected carrier dogs could be adversely affected by medications comprising the immune system (such as steroids), or by an illness possibly reducing a dog's immune status. Source: https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/anaplasmosis-in-dogs - Mod.TG

